    "summary": "With 20 years of experience in songwriting and music production, some projects can be found in the internet: Marcio Hendrik (solo), Artigo Audio (Label? Collective? Publisher? Alter-ego?), Basttardos, Delta Rock, Canalhocratas (a.k.a Scoundrelcrats), Domestic Junkies, Fio Desencapado (a.k.a Bare Wire), Ferradura (Horse Shoe), Noise Punch and 8 Grave. They all fit into Alternative Rock, inspired by Grunge and Psychedelic sounds. I've graduated in bass at Villa Lobos Music School of Rio de Janeiro. Playing bass, writing music and producing, my creativity expanded with Savanna (more than a band, a collective): I performed to five thousand people in a stadium, won a prize of best-instrumentalist and reached deeper conclusions about life with psychedelic trips before/during and after our jam sessions. Influenced by The Velvet Underground, Jimi Hendrix, Black Sabbath, The Doors and Nirvana. We recorded jams and listened after; then we would improve the next recording. It was our writing process. We were proud to represent the Rio de Janeiro underground music scene. Suddenly, I moved to Hollywood to study audio engineering at the Musicians Institute (M.I). One year later, back to town, a crisis emerged: The band split (fellow musicians went to do other jobs), my family moved to Lisbon and I was switching between the U.S, Brazil and Portugal. Giving sequence to musical works, I wished to become \u201ca citizen of the world\u201d. With up to three hundred recordings and a non-stop growing catalog, my skills as a composer grew along with my studies. I currently study Music Business at Berklee, where I am able to develop and \u201cdesign\u201d new perspectives. Thanks to them, I was able to broaden my spectrum, and also get an internship at Wisseloord Studios in The Netherlands (A top-notch studio founded in 1978; it hosted acts like David Lee Roth, Def Leppard, Electric Light Orchestra, Elton John, Focus, Foo Fighters, Frankie Goes to Hollywood, Iron Maiden, Jeff Lyne, Judas Priest, Metallica, Michael Jackson, Mick Jagger, Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark, Paco de Lucia, Paul McCartney, Phil Collins, Robert Palmer, Sade, Scorpions, Shirley Bassey, Simple Minds, Simply Red, Sinead O\u2019 Connor, Sting/The Police, Tina Turner, Toots Thielemans, U2 and UB40). I have a healthy competition with major publishers. I wish to write better music than their roster. If you feel me, greetings! Hit me up and let\u2019s collab.",
